The paper deals with motion planning for a robot in cluttered and uncertain environments, which is a common problem in robotics. The use of a physics engine to evaluate possible complex multi-body dynamical interactions suggests that the paper belongs to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes an enhanced algorithm that improves the state validity checker, the control sampler, and the tree exploration strategy of a kinodynamic motion planner, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and systems and control (cs.SY) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of computer vision techniques to detect objects in the environment, which suggests that the paper may belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the paper compares its results with other motion planning approaches, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
